  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM is a psychological phenomenon where individuals from groups historically marginalized in science and technology experience anxiety or reduced performance due to the belief that they are judged based on stereotypes about their group's abilities. As an immigrant who spent much of his life in Chicago and witnessed the educational struggles of my children and grandchildren, I've seen how this issue plays out in classrooms and labs. For instance, when young students from underrepresented backgrounds hear that 'only certain types of people can be good at math,' it can create a self-fulfilling prophecy that hinders their potential. The anxiety stemming from these stereotypes is not just a theoretical concern—it's real and deeply personal. I believe we must address it through systemic changes, not just individual efforts. Schools should implement programs that explicitly challenge stereotypes and promote inclusive learning environments. Universities need to create mentorship networks that connect students with role models who share their backgrounds. Moreover, teachers must be trained to recognize and mitigate the effects of stereotype threat in the classroom. My own anxiety about fitting in during my early education years in the U.S. reminds me that these issues affect everyone, regardless of background. While it's true that some students may be more resilient than others, the system as a whole must evolve to ensure that everyone has the opportunity to thrive in STEM fields. We cannot afford to let the fear of stereotypes prevent talented individuals from pursuing their dreams.",
